<Rate>5< /Rate><review>Yesterday, my girlfriend and I left our house with no intention of buying a new mattress or even looking at them.  Though we had talked about it a few times in the recent past, we were not in a hurry to make any such purchase.  But, after leaving the Yuba City Walmart, we noticed very interesting signs. The signs described great deals at Mattress Firm.  Because we were not in any hurry to go back home, we walked to Mattress Firm to learn more.  When we were arrived we were greeted five fairy friendly associate, Jaun.  Right from the beginning, it was a no pressure environment. He just explained how the process works when shopping for mattresses and what features to keep in mind.  He then provided us with advice on which beds to test.  Though several felt fantastic, my girlfriend and I settled on the Midnight Intellibed.  We notified Juan that we were interested to learn more about the bed and we sat down with him to discuss it‚Äôs cost. Thankfully, he informed us that there was a California king-sized bed available.  It apparently was returned due to buyers remorse and that we can purchase it for nearly half price.  Though we were slightly uneasy about buying a (supposedly) slightly-used bed, we were comforted by the fact that we were told that we can refuse shipment if we see anything wrong with it when it is delivered to our house.  We were doubtful that there would be any structure issues with such a object and we read about California laws which require mattresses to be sanitized before for any resale.  For these reasons, we decided to go ahead and make the purchase. It only took a few minutes for Juan and his awesome associate (I forgot his name) to put in the paperwork.  Now, we have only days to wait for our new bed to arrive and sweet dreams to look forward to.< /review>< pictures>

< review>

Before beginning the work, the dentist asked if I had considered braces(I have small gaps between my teeth) and said she'd set up a consultation with an orthodontist. During my procedure she began separating my teeth and said that it wouldn't matter since I would be getting braces anyways. Mind you, I had only agreed to the free consultation and never even remotely suggested I was interested in them. Ms car salesmen refused to take no for an answer. Whatever.

A few weeks have gone by since they did the work and the side they performed work on is super sensitive to the point where I am no longer able to chew. Needless to say, this was not the case prior to visiting them.<//review>

Do not go here. I work in the medical field and I wouldn't usually write a negative review on a medical establishment but I am appalled at how I was treated here. The first time I visited this office they had no idea what they were doing as far as my insurance was concerned, I took the morning off work for my new patient exam and didn't even get in to see the dentist for 4 hours because that's how long it took the front desk to figure out my insurance coverage...only AFTER I called the insurance company myself were they able to get it together. They took my radiographs and I saw a relatively nice male dentist who wanted to talk to me about cleanings, fillings, and braces which is unfortunately not what I was there for. I needed my wisdom teeth removed. They didn't do any work on my mouth that day. They shuffled me into the finance office and Norma proceeded to break down how much oral surgery was going to cost me. She asked me what kind of anesthesia I wanted; what my pain tolerance was? The end result according to Norma was that my procedure including anesthesia would cost $437, and I scheduled it for the following Friday. Fast forward to Friday morning at 7:30am both my girlfriend and I took the day off for my oral surgery. I checked in with the front desk. The receptionist proceeded to ask me how I was being anesthetized? Why they didn't know this already I wasn't sure. I told her that I spoke with Norma at my last appointment and we scheduled sedation and extractions, she told me not to eat after midnight, and to bring someone with me to help me get back home. The receptionist then tells me their financial manager Norma, MISQUOTED me and my procedure was actually going to cost $900. Excuse me? They then proceeded to tell me that it was "okay" because they can finance me...it is NOT okay. They gave a credit for to fill out while I waited 2 hours in the waiting room (starving) waiting for Norma to come in. I DID NOT want their mistake affecting my credit. Norma finally arrived and she admitted to her mistake, said she "assumed" my PPO insurance was going to cover my sedation. I was still liable for $800. We agreed on a payment plan, $430 down and 2 more payments over the next two months, no credit necessary. I went into surgery and came out only to find out that our lovely friend Norma had run my credit while I was asleep after I repeatedly told her not to, told me it was protocol and had me sign all the forms while I was coming out of sedation which I am pretty sure is illegal. Worst experience I've ever had at a medical office of any kind.</review>

< username>
Jacob Varshavsky< /username>
< Time>
1572500689348< /Time>
< rating>
5</rating>
< Review>
A very well taken care of place of business that makes me proud to be a San Franciscan (if modesty and pride go together) you can tell that the sign has been there for a while, qualifies as at least vintage if not historic, and blends in well with the surroundings.

Don't let that fool you - they run a very tight game and care about what they serve to the community and the merchandise is caught up with modern demand.

You can find all the remedies you need to replenish your gut bacteria (kombucha, yogurt, etc) after a good night out as well as classic junk food items! (Chips, jerky, candy)

Overall, the team goes above and beyond a regular store-n-deli deal and I leave feeling good about spending my money at Ted's!

And for people that LOVE to read:
That combination of modesty and top-notch cutting edge service is a characteristic of true SF places that have been around - respect for the neighborhoods history.
I personally appreciate that because while it is useless to resist the inevitable and everyone has their own past - our children will have to share the future.
Sort of a reminder to avoid judging the book by its cover and to remember what you're stepping on, because once it's gone - it's gone!</Review>

<UserId.>103737576089759430540< /UserId.>< username>
Jack Kelley</username>
<Time>1565906063261< /Time><rate>5</rate>< review>
This place is fantastic, a hidden GEM. In SOMA's ocean of $14+ sandwich places, this place not only sells a veritable smorgasbord of preposterously fresh sandwiches for less than you'd pay at Subway, but the guy who runs the place is the friendly sort of neighborhood shop owner you rarely see outside of old movies. He actually seems to know his customers, and the staff is similarly cheerful. After I ordered a meatball sub on Dutch crunch bread (the freshest and best I've ever had), the owner asked if I'd had one from them before. Learning I hadn't, he gave me a big stack of napkins and a fork with a knowing "You're gonna need these". A+ for the kind of customer attention I'm sure it's not easy to keep up all day. From the sign street it looks like a typical corner shop, but it's definitely not. Give this place all your sandwich-related business. And they sell booze too!</review>

WEDDING CATERING - I just attended a wedding at which Ted's Deli catered the food for 150 guests.  On top of the over-the-top customer service of David delivering the order himself, Ted's selected a menu that required no heating or refrigeration for the short duration between delivery and serving time which certainly helped with the logistics and clean up. The family and guests were delighted with the food and ate every bite by the end of the party.  I give Ted's Six Stars if they were an option!< /review>

<gmap_id>0x808f7e277b7d3ce5:0x3efd007a2bbfc62</gmap_id>< Name>
Charles Dexter Lim</Name>
<Time>1423299846276</Time>< text>
One of the best places to get a sandwich in the Civic Center/Van Ness area of San Francisco. The line could take a while during lunch (be prepared to wait 10-15 minutes if not more, as you'll have that many people in front of you if you're there around 12 noon). The line fairly moves quickly though and then you get a fully loaded sandwich (assuming you get everything on it), and real turkey as an option instead of deli turkey if you're into eating turkey.

No place for sitting down, so it's all about the food on this place. Great tasting sandwiches costing around $7 as of writing can't be beat!</text>

< Date>
1377667634902<//Date>
< rate>
5</rate>
< Text>
Ted's is not for everyone, but I really enjoy spending time there. The owner is incredibly nice and friendly, and truly treats you like family.

The food is quite good and the prices more than fair. Ted's has lots of cool sports memorabilia decorating the walls, and the place was recently remodeled into a sports bar feel. There's a high-def TV every which way you look, and cozy booths as well so you can enjoy it with a medium sized party.

Because it's a family-run establishment, service tends to be a bit slow, but the experience is still great because the servers are so personable. I really liked their wings (although spicier than I expected), and the cheeseburger and fries are a strong classic.< /Text>

<UserId.>115078328947075721595<//UserId.><username>Robert Ogawa-Monroe</username><Time>1619043128281<//Time>< rating>
4</rating>
< review>
Interesting presentation displays of local historical events early in the days when Monterey Park developed.  Including the starts of well-known names like Laura Schudders.
Other exhibits highlight collections of Monterey Park Historical Society

* I would like to see much more specifically about the significance of the actual Observatory itself.
Pertaining to "hobbies" of the wealthy, there's a rich history to tell of the many influential persons in the history of Los Angeles and Southern California who's interests, studies and wealth contributed to the advancement of significant astronomical and scientific discoveries.
-- From Griffith Park, Mount Wilson, Saddle Back, Palomar, JPL, CalTech... many peoples involved within and around the San Gabriel Valley.<//review>

<Rating>5< /Rating><name>Jeannette G.< /name>< time>
1399426768848</time>
<text>This is my go-to tire shop.  I went in to VItness to get one of my tires checked out - it had a screw in it.

Once I parked in the garage, the owner came out to inquire about the service I needed.  I told him about the screw in the tire and he said that because the screw was on the side of the tire, there was nothing that could be done to repair it.

FYI- if you get a screw/nail in your tire, that tire is reparable only if it is on the thread (middle of the tire).  If it is on the side, it is not reparable and a new tire is needed.

I verified this information using my smart phone - hey you never know...I certainly didn't.

The guy said he'd pull it out with the hope that just on the surface and hence no replacement would be needed.  Alas, that was not the case, as when he started pulling the screw out, the tire started deflating.

The unfortunate thing is I had just replaced my tires no more than a year ago - still lots of miles to go.

The entire replacement of my tire was $85 including tax.  Overall, the service was done professionally and quickly.  I was in/out in 20 minutes.</text><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< userid>
104636687373132435944<//userid>

< Review>
A pretty decent church, I'd say. Looks nice, and is pretty spacious.
My biggest complaint however, lies with the pastor for the 5pm English session(s). His accent is VERY heavy, which makes it hard to understand what he's trying to say. I at most could pick out 2-3 words at a time, often leaving me wondering what exactly he was trying to preach.
Also, while not nearly as hindering, this church doesn't have air conditioning. They open the windows, but it still leaves the room kinda warm. I just figured I should mention it for those with a sensitivity to heat.</Review>

< text>
I came to visit the Blessed Sacrament, and I found out that at his chapel, they have the most adorable image of our Lady brought from Europe that should be exposed as well in the main church.
A complete piece of Art, that in my consideration is hidden from the world in that small chapel.
If you are in the vicinity of El Segundo, PLEASE STOP by this chapel and enjoy a jewel of the Sacred Art, assure you that you won't be dissapointed!!!!</text>

<Review>If you're looking for a very good orthodox teaching in Catholicism this is the place to be.  Fr. Robert is a great shepherd of the flock along with the associate priests.  We cannot thank them enough for their priesthood and their ministry.  These men are great gifts to the community.
Also, for Catholics who have plenty of questions to their faith, there's the bible study every Monday at 7pm in the parish center.  You will love our Lord even more as you know Him.  If we only realize it, there is not enough time in this life to fully know our GOD. Best kept secret in San Diego. This Urgent care is the best. The staff and doctors are amazing, almost no wait time. <rating>5</rating>< review>
At 57 years old, I have seen my fair share of doctors.   I am in good health and have always received fairly good care.  But, I can tell you, the doctor that I saw at Sharp was absolutely the best.

After experiencing a minor vision incident, my wife insisted that I go to a doctor. Having no doctor available within the system, I visited the urgent care area at Sharp. I was assigned Dr. Karen Tipler.

From the moment the doctor started to assess my situation, I had the confidence that she was really analyzing the situation and doing a thorough examination.  She asked pointed questions and explained her reasoning - all the while methodically eliminating possible diagnosis which she was clear was not the cause.

When all was said and done, I left the care center with a full body of blood work, a full eye examination and a referral to another specialist as a further precaution.

Later that evening the Dr. personally called me as a follow up to our conversation.  After having already believed she had afforded me great care, she had no idea how appreciative I was that she did that follow up.  It further convinced me that Dr Tipler was a cut above the rest.

This is a Dr. that truly cares about her patients, has a wide range of knowledge and takes her time to make sure she gets it right.

Sharp likewise has a comprehensive system designed to give total care.</review>

Went to the Urgent Care department and was pleasantly surprised at how everyone was so nice in the department. I was actually accompanying a family member and didn't deal with any of the nurses, although I also received very good feedback from them too, but the Front Desk staff was great, especially Annette and Sheryl. They had noticed that I had been waiting for a while for my family member to come back out from care and they asked me if I was okay. When I asked if there was a vending machine (I was starving and on the verge of fainting!!!!!), instead of telling me that there wasn't any on site for customers they took me to the employee lounge. Also, I didn't have any change on me, just my debit card but Annette and Sheryl didn't hesitate one bit to buy me something from the machine. It's those little gestures that make all the difference in customer service and I wanted to make those ladies noticed! hopefully this comment will go to management.
I would like to thank those ladies again for their great service and genuine kindness but also recommend this great Urgent Care facility.< /text>

< Text>
Need to get a Hep B vaccine for my new position so went to Sharp Rees-Stealy Occupational Medicine department. The staff on the front desk were very friendly and arranged a lab test quickly. Again, the lady on the front desk of lab was nice. Waiting time was less than 10 min. However, the staff who took my blood was unfriendly. No smiles, no greetings, no thanks, no whatsoever. Seems she just wanted to get me out asap. By the way, there was no one after me, so I don't know why she rushed so much. Maybe she happened to be in a bad mood that day, but feeling unwelcome when I left was not what I expected. This is why I give 3 stars.<//Text>
